dismissalText.long: c Nawroz Mangal b Dawlat Zadran
dismissalText.commentary: Craig Ervine c Nawroz Mangal b Dawlat Zadran 73 (98b 7x4 1x6) SR: 74.48

dismissalComment.html: what has he done here? A harmless full toss outside off has been hit straight to deep cover. Nothing delivery, nothing shot, really. He backs himself to clear the fielder there, hits it well but it almost seems like he forgot there was a fielder in the deep. He may have also got it a lot squarer than he would have liked. The umpire's checked for the no-ball and it seems fine. So Ervine has to make the long walk back. That is a gift.

headshotImage.caption: Mohammad Shahzad player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Mohammad Shahzad player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Peter Moor st †Mohammad Shahzad b Mohammad Nabi 50 (51b 5x4 3x6) SR: 98.03

dismissalComment.html: Shahzad is ecstatic, he is sure he has his man. Pushed through wide outside off, Moor goes for the drive and is beaten. Shahzad does very well to whip off the bails and Moor's back foot is on the line. Shahzad's quick work earns Afghanistan their first wicket. Good stuff.

what has he done here? A harmless full toss outside off has been hit straight to deep cover. Nothing delivery, nothing shot, really. He backs himself to clear the fielder there, hits it well but it almost seems like he forgot there was a fielder in the deep. He may have also got it a lot squarer than he would have liked. The umpire's checked for the no-ball and it seems fine. So Ervine has to make the long walk back. That is a gift.

Lasith Malinga would have been proud of that yorker. Full, and dead straight, the ball tails back in just a wee bit, he was already through with the big swing, couldn't connect as the ball cannoned into the middle stump. Is there a better sight than seeing a fast bowler rattle the stumps? Me thinks not

looked to clear the boundary, but the elevation was missing, didn't get enough power behind that one as the ball lodges in the hands of the long-off fielder. He didn't have to move an inch to take that dolly.

he's launched that into orbit, but a good effort by Nabi at long-on steals the thunder. It was right in the slot for him to go for the big hit, didn't perhaps get the elevation he wanted even though he struck it well, and Nabi balanced himself nicely to take the rocket hit.

dismissalText.commentary: Hamilton Masakadza b Mohammad Nabi 47 (64b 4x4 0x6) SR: 73.43

dismissalComment.html: done in by slow turn this time. The pressure was building and Masakadza has fallen into the trap. His eyes lit up as the delivery was tossed up over his eye line, stepped out to go over long-on, swung a little too early, was completely deceived in flight as the ball spun back in to hit the stumps. Big wicket for Afghanistan. Could be a big moment in the innings too, for Zimbabwe

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Nabi run out (WP Masakadza/Chigumbura) 33 (36b 4x4 0x6) SR: 91.66

dismissalComment.html: gone! What a sad way to go. Nabi has totally misjudged the second run and he has to go. Shahzad is left shaking his head. Worked away towards long-on and Shahzad scampers the first, Nabi doesn't hesitate for the second and runs back but the throw was good - on the bounce to the bowler just over the stumps. The bowler collected and whipped off the bails to find Nabi more than a foot short.

bowled im. Chigumbura strikes. Chigs enjoys a jig. Shortish delivery outside off, Stanikzai goes for a full-blooded cut but the ball stops and grips in the pitch, and takes the inside edge before clattering into the stumps.

another one for Chigs. Inzy isn't impressed. Shenwari goes now. Nips one back in and sneaks through a big gap between bat and pad and uproots the middle stump. Not much Shenwari could have done about that, no wonder there is a look of amazement on his face. He has to go though. Chigumbura's self-introduction into the attack has changed the complexion of this game.

gone! Another one goes. Chigs gets another. A slower ball on off and middle, Najibullah goes for a pull but gets a leading edge which lobs up int he air for midwicket to take. And a great catch too, he backtracked and took  a hard catch over his head running back.

dismissalComment.html: there's the breakthrough for Zimbabwe. He got to the pitch of the ball, timed it nicely, did most things right, but Craig Ervine, at long-on, had his eyes on the ball, while also knowing where the rope was behind him, before completing the catch. Big wicket against the run of play at a time when Afghanistan were slowly eating into the target

commentTextItems.html: the wild slog doesn't go where he intended, but he still manages to beat mid-on to the boundary. Shahzad starts off on his celebratory jig. The normally subdued Inzamam is all smiles. The entire team is on their feet. Zimbabwe absolutely gutted. What a thriller this has been

commentPostTextItems.html: Thanks for joining us. Hope you enjoyed the coverage, which we certainly enjoyed bringing it to you. Join us for the third ODI on January 2. Until then, it's goodbye from all of us here at the commentary desk. Cheers!

Asghar Stanikzai: Great game, delighted with our performance. Openers started well, unfortunately our middle order struggled. Hopefully we will fire in the next game. Match became a lot tougher because we lost a few wickets. Shahzad's knock was brilliant.

Elton Chigumbura: Maybe 20 more runs could have made the difference. It was going to be difficult for the bowlers because there wasn't much assistance. We could have churned out more singles while batting. It's always good to reach milestones (4000 runs and 100 wickets), but the important thing was to win the game. I thought the wicket played better, the way Shahzad batted showed how easy it was one you got in on this surface.

No prizes for guessing who the Player of the Match is. "Before this series, we had a 14-day fitness camp, perhaps that's done the trick," says Mohammad Shahzad. "The ball didn't come onto the bat, so the plan was to bat till the end. The bowlers did a good job on this surface. Two consecutive wins against a Test team is a proud moment for us."
Just to clarify, a single was completed before the ball went to the boundary. And so the game ends there, even though the ball eventually crossed the line

10:32 pm local Mirwais Ashraf's cameo can't be understated either. Should have been out lbw, but wasn't given. But he cashed in and ensured he was there till the end along with Shahzad as Afghanistan clinched a game they could have won much more comfortably, if not for a batting meltdown. Elton Chigumbura, who doesn't bowl much these days in ODIs, brought himself on to pick up three wickets, but Zimbabwe were to be denied by one man. What a character Shahzad is!

10:30pm local Mohammad Shahzad, take a bow. Kept for 50 overs in the heat, then came out, made a century and carried his bat through in a tough chase, where Afghanistan were challenged at different times. What looked like a cruise suddenly became a little nervy as they lost a clutch of wickets, but Shahzad's steely determination and exuberance has seen them home. The 2-0 lead also means Afghanistan will end 2015 ranked No. 10 in the ICC ODI charts. The Afghanistan flag flies high.

commentPreTextItems.html: Right, can Shahzad do an MS and finish this off with a six?

commentTextItems.html: length ball on off, he backs away and slaps it over cover. That now is the highest score by an Afghanistan batsman in ODIs
gets a thick inside edge as the slog rolls into the gap between deep midwicket and wide long-on. The 50 partnership is up too
full but sprays it down leg, looking to follow the batsman, unsuccessful
Ashraf wanted the single, Shahzad sent him back, could have been chaotic if the fielder running in from point hit direct at the non-striker's end

slower ball and he's picked his spot to perfection. It was right in the slot for Ashraf to unfurl the big hit, he swung clean and picked the gap at cow corner. Afghanistan inch ever so close to a 2-0 lead

commentTextItems.html: firm drive, the cover fielder managed a half-stop and the deflection rolled towards long-off, that allowed them to complete the second

commentPreTextItems.html: Ven: "Except for those nervous 90s.. MS has been impressive in most of his innings.. Clearing ropes with ease at important situations of the game.. Well played!"

commentTextItems.html: right into the blockhole from wide of the crease, keeps that out
squeezed away behind point, no one in the deep and that's four more to the total.
low full toss outside off, slapped to deep cover where Sikandar Raza moves swiftly to fire a rocket throw
full and just a touch outside off, Shahzad plays an ugly swipe, but can't connect
padded away back down the pitch

commentTextItems.html: plays and misses, squared up by sharp turn
gets forward and turns it across the line towards long-on
tossed up over his eye-line and Shahzad says 'thank you very much.' Makes room, generates enough power, swings through the line and crashes that over long-off. Picked the bones out of that one
frees his arms and thumps it to long-off
spins away from middle, he gets an inside edge as he looks to defend
looks to step out and go over midwicket, but can't generate power off the bottom hand, rolls to the midwicket fielder. Get the feeling that Shahzad is starting to cramp a bit

dismissalText.commentary: Craig Ervine c Nawroz Mangal b Dawlat Zadran 73 (98b 7x4 1x6) SR: 74.48

dismissalComment.html: what has he done here? A harmless full toss outside off has been hit straight to deep cover. Nothing delivery, nothing shot, really. He backs himself to clear the fielder there, hits it well but it almost seems like he forgot there was a fielder in the deep. He may have also got it a lot squarer than he would have liked. The umpire's checked for the no-ball and it seems fine. So Ervine has to make the long walk back. That is a gift.

dismissalText.commentary: Malcolm Waller b Dawlat Zadran 0 (1b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: Lasith Malinga would have been proud of that yorker. Full, and dead straight, the ball tails back in just a wee bit, he was already through with the big swing, couldn't connect as the ball cannoned into the middle stump. Is there a better sight than seeing a fast bowler rattle the stumps? Me thinks not

dismissalText.long: c Mohammad Nabi b Dawlat Zadran
dismissalText.commentary: Sikandar Raza c Mohammad Nabi b Dawlat Zadran 13 (9b 2x4 0x6) SR: 144.44

dismissalComment.html: looked to clear the boundary, but the elevation was missing, didn't get enough power behind that one as the ball lodges in the hands of the long-off fielder. He didn't have to move an inch to take that dolly.

dismissalText.commentary: Noor Ali Zadran c Ervine b Sikandar Raza 31 (52b 3x4 0x6) SR: 59.61

dismissalComment.html: there's the breakthrough for Zimbabwe. He got to the pitch of the ball, timed it nicely, did most things right, but Craig Ervine, at long-on, had his eyes on the ball, while also knowing where the rope was behind him, before completing the catch. Big wicket against the run of play at a time when Afghanistan were slowly eating into the target

headshotImage.longCaption: Mohammad Shahzad player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Shahzad not out 131 (133b 7x4 8x6) SR: 98.49

headshotImage.caption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Nabi run out (WP Masakadza/Chigumbura) 33 (36b 4x4 0x6) SR: 91.66

dismissalComment.html: gone! What a sad way to go. Nabi has totally misjudged the second run and he has to go. Shahzad is left shaking his head. Worked away towards long-on and Shahzad scampers the first, Nabi doesn't hesitate for the second and runs back but the throw was good - on the bounce to the bowler just over the stumps. The bowler collected and whipped off the bails to find Nabi more than a foot short.

dismissalText.commentary: Nawroz Mangal c & b Cremer 8 (14b 1x4 0x6) SR: 57.14

dismissalComment.html: gone! Mangal's stumbling innings has finally ended. Tossed up nicely on off and Mangal was persistent in trying to play against the turn to the legspinner. He gets a big of a leading edge back to the bowler who takes a sitter and Mangal has to go.

dismissalText.commentary: Asghar Afghan b Chigumbura 1 (2b 0x4 0x6) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: bowled im. Chigumbura strikes. Chigs enjoys a jig. Shortish delivery outside off, Stanikzai goes for a full-blooded cut but the ball stops and grips in the pitch, and takes the inside edge before clattering into the stumps.

dismissalText.commentary: Samiullah Shinwari b Chigumbura 4 (14b 0x4 0x6) SR: 28.57

dismissalComment.html: another one for Chigs. Inzy isn't impressed. Shenwari goes now. Nips one back in and sneaks through a big gap between bat and pad and uproots the middle stump. Not much Shenwari could have done about that, no wonder there is a look of amazement on his face. He has to go though. Chigumbura's self-introduction into the attack has changed the complexion of this game.

dismissalText.commentary: Najibullah Zadran c sub (CJ Chibhabha) b Chigumbura 9 (8b 1x4 0x6) SR: 112.5

dismissalComment.html: gone! Another one goes. Chigs gets another. A slower ball on off and middle, Najibullah goes for a pull but gets a leading edge which lobs up int he air for midwicket to take. And a great catch too, he backtracked and took  a hard catch over his head running back.

dismissalText.commentary: Mirwais Ashraf not out 26 (27b 1x4 2x6) SR: 96.29

milestones.description: Shahzad has broken the record for most runs in boundaries (76) in an innings in ODIs for AFG, going past Karim Sadiq's 72
Shahzad's 131 is the highest individual score in ODIs (for AFG), surpassing Nawroz Mangal's 129
Shahzad has broken the record for most sixes in an innings (8) in ODIs for AFG, going past Nawroz Mangal's 6
Dawlat Zadran has broken the record for most ducks (4) in ODIs for AFG, going past Nawroz Mangal's 4
